spans.text: how the Lark and Linnet jointly sing
with my Tears increase the falling Dew
the Weight of Age sustain , When , as our waining Strength does daily cease
Spite of my snowy Head and icy Veins : For , why should Man at cross Mishaps repine , Sour all his Sweet , and mix with Tears his Wine
his Sweet , and mix with Tears his Wine
a Friend thy inward Ailment know
of Storms and Sport of every Wind
longing Eyes review thy flowery Shore
My Face , grown won through Care and Misery
my Hut , the small Abode My self had raised and covered over with Sod
I know not what , besides a Name
their Keeper , ragged grown and bare
It's hard to bear the pinching Cold with Pain , And hard
pelting Showers Destroy the tender Herb and budding Flowers
the tender Herb and budding Flowers
Mock of all the Ditties I endite
what thou wilt , ill Nature will prevail
